    79	## Q2 — Back-compat policy when Commander deprecates a flag DSK relies on
    80	
    81	**Decision: 2-version overlap window. When upstream deprecates, DSK keeps
    82	the old behaviour for at least 2 Commander pin bumps (typically ~6-12
    83	weeks) under a `deprecated_in: <commander-sha>` annotation in the matrix.**
    84	
    85	Mechanism:
    86	
    87	1. `sync_upstream.py --check` flags removed flags as `WARNING (deprecated)` for
    88	   the first pin-bump cycle, `ERROR (removed)` from the third bump onward.
    89	2. Each schema field with a deprecated upstream backing carries
    90	   `"x-keeper-deprecated": {"since-pin": "<sha>", "remove-after-pin": "<sha>",
    91	   "reason": "..."}` in the schema JSON. `dsk validate` emits a warning
    92	   stage-3 message; `dsk plan` emits a comment in the diff.
    93	3. Hard removals require a new schema major (`v2`) + 12-week deprecation
    94	   notice in `CHANGELOG.md` + a `migrate <from> <to>` CLI helper.
    95	
    96	Owner: parent decides which removed flag triggers schema major; codex
    97	worker mechanically emits the warnings.
    98	
    99	## Q3 — Which runtime-only categories get `dsk` passthrough surface
   100	
   101	**Decision: ship `dsk run <commander-cmd>` (single passthrough verb) AND
   102	`dsk report <commander-cmd>` (read-with-redaction verb). NOT a per-command
   103	verb each.**
   104	
   105	Two verbs because their semantics differ:
   106	
   107	| Verb | Wraps | Output | Redaction | Examples |
   108	|---|---|---|---|---|
   109	| `dsk run` | runtime/session commands that mutate / launch / open | streams to TTY, exit code passed through | minimal — caller asked for it | `connect`, `tunnel start/stop`, `pam launch`, `supershell`, `ssh-agent`, `service start` |
   110	| `dsk report` | read-only commands that emit JSON or report tables | captured, parsed, redacted, printed | full — strip secret fields, mask UIDs in `--quiet` | `aram audit-report`, `compliance-report`, `security-audit-report`, `password-report`, `record-totp`, `enterprise-reports`, `device-management list` |
   111	
   112	Out of scope for both: anything in the dropped-design column (msp,
   113	distributor, two_fa enrollment, verify_records, convert) — those need a
   114	product decision before any wrapper ships. `pam_debug` stays out;
   115	debug surfaces are not for end users.
   116	
   117	## Q4 — Live-proof per phase or batched at v2.0
   118	
   119	**Decision: per-phase, gated by the schema-family declaration.**
   120	
   121	Each `<family>.<version>` schema must carry one of:
   122	
   123	```jsonc
   124	"x-keeper-live-proof": {
   125	  "status": "supported" | "preview-gated" | "upstream-gap",
   126	  "evidence": "<path to live-proof transcript or 'pending'>",
   127	  "since-pin": "<commander-sha>"
   128	}
   129	```
   130	
   131	Rationale: batching at v2.0 means no public release for the entire
   132	duration of P9-P18 (likely 6+ months of work). Per-phase keeps the
   133	release cadence small + makes regressions caught at the phase boundary,
   134	not at v2.0 RC.
   135	
   136	Each phase's PR includes a `proof-transcript.md` referenced from the
   137	schema's `evidence` field. Parent owns the live tenant; codex owns the
   138	transcript review against expected JSON.
   139	
   140	## Q5 — MSP and EPM in product scope
   141	
   142	**Decision:**
   143	
   144	- **MSP** → **dropped-design (watch-only).** Un-drop trigger: parent
   145	  acquires an MSP tenant for testing AND a customer asks for declarative
   146	  MSP. Until both, sync_upstream tracks MSP commands but no schema work.
   147	- **EPM (PEDM)** → **scope kept; P16 stays in the roadmap.** Triggers
   148	  for actual implementation: (a) `pedm_admin.py` source audit lands a
   149	  capability snapshot, (b) at least one EPM customer of DSK exists, (c)
   150	  CI runs a fresh PEDM-licensed tenant smoke. Until all three, P16 is a
   151	  watchlist row only — no schema until audit lands.
   152	
   153	The asymmetry: MSP requires a special tenant license that's parent-side
   154	overhead with no current demand; EPM is part of standard enterprise
   155	tenants we already test against, so the audit is cheap and the schema
   156	work has a defensible ROI.
   157	
   158	## Q6 — Definition of "all of Commander"
   159	
   160	**Decision: 137 statically registered command roots, machine-counted via
   161	the `register_commands` family of functions across the Commander tree.**
   162	
   163	This is the unit of coverage P18's extractor maintains. The extractor
   164	counts:
   165	
   166	- `keepercommander.commands.base.commands[<name>]` registrations in every
   167	  `register_*_commands` function.
   168	- Nested `GroupCommand` trees expanded one level (so `pam connection edit`
   169	  counts as a leaf, not as `pam connection`).
   170	- External register paths: `keepercommander.importer.commands.register_commands`,
   171	  `keepercommander.plugins.commands.register_commands`,
