174:   174	- 2026-04-26 [schema][scaffold-only-status] **New schema families should ship as scaffold-only stubs with `x-keeper-live-proof.status: "scaffold-only"` BEFORE any body is written, so consumers can pin the family name + version without false-claiming functionality.** Sprint 7h-12: 8 V2 families landed as scaffold-only — each has `const "<family>.v1"` for the `schema` key + `additionalProperties: false` so any manifest declaring the family today is rejected with a clean error pointing at the scaffold-only status. Beats two alternatives: (a) "land the family directory empty, no schema file" — consumers can't even pin the family, so versioning is ambiguous; (b) "land a permissive schema accepting `{}`" — silently passes validation today, fails at apply with a confusing "no provider" error. Scaffold-only is the explicit, self-documenting middle path. Pattern: any "we'll implement X later" announcement that ships a directory should also ship a stub with a const-locked identity + a `scaffold-only` annotation, never an empty file.
184:   184	- 2026-04-24 [validate][protocol] **Split "can this tenant even execute the manifest" into the provider Protocol, not the CLI.** Stage 5 of `validate --online` was printing a plan summary and calling itself done. The right shape wasn't to stuff more checks into `cli/main.py::validate`; it was to add `Provider.check_tenant_bindings(manifest) -> list[str]` as a Protocol method with a sensible default (mock returns `[]`), and let each provider implement the checks it can cheaply make (commander: one `pam gateway list` + one `pam config list` round-trip, four invariants verified — config title resolves, shared_folder_uid present, gateway pairing matches, KSM app name matches). Every issue is returned as a plain string; the CLI aggregates + prints them all (not first-fail) and exits `EXIT_CAPABILITY`. Rule: if a check is provider-specific but semantically "can this manifest bind to this tenant", it belongs on the Provider protocol, not on the CLI. Same reason `unsupported_capabilities()` is there.
185:   185	- 2026-04-24 [testing][smoke] **Extract live-only scenarios into an offline-testable registry.** The original live-smoke was a 576-line monolith pinned to pamMachine — every new resource type meant forking the whole flow. Fix: create `scripts/smoke/scenarios.py` with `ScenarioSpec(name, resource_type, build_resources, verify)` objects, keep the identity/sandbox/destroy flow invariant, parametrise via `--scenario NAME`. The payoff is `tests/test_smoke_scenarios.py`: every scenario's `build_resources()` output goes through schema + typed-model + planner **without a tenant**, so schema drift (missing `url` on `pamRemoteBrowser`, wrong `database_type` enum) fails in milliseconds in CI instead of burning a tenant round-trip. Deferred scenarios (pamUser-standalone, adoption, drift, two-writer race) noted in V1_GA_CHECKLIST — the registry is the hosting pattern for them. Rule: when a live-only test runner accepts parametrisation, split the variant into a data object and test the variant offline through as much of the production pipeline as it touches.
195:   195	- 2026-04-24 [sdk][capability][protocol] **Surface capability gaps as plan rows, not apply exceptions.** First pass put the capability guard inside `CommanderCliProvider.apply_plan` — that guaranteed `apply` would refuse unimplemented fields, but left `plan` and `apply --dry-run` green for the exact same input. DOR promises `plan == apply --dry-run == apply`; we were quietly violating it. Fix: add `unsupported_capabilities(manifest) -> list[str]` to the `Provider` protocol, call it from the CLI's `_build_plan`, prepend a `ChangeKind.CONFLICT` row per reason. `apply_plan` keeps the raise as a last-line defence for SDK callers that skip the CLI. Pattern is reusable: any guard that belongs to a provider should be a protocol method the orchestration layer can call before committing, not a method the orchestration layer discovers by catching.
