     1	# Commander dependency pin
     2	
     3	The SDK shells out to the **Keeper Commander** CLI (`keeper`) and imports its
     4	Python module in-process for a handful of commands. This page documents the
     5	exact version we target, the deltas vs older binaries operators may still
     6	have on disk, and the subset of Commander capabilities the SDK relies on.
     7	
     8	## Target version
     9	
    10	| artefact | version | reference |
    11	|----------|---------|-----------|
    12	| Python module (`keepercommander`) | `17.2.13` tag + ~40 commits on `upstream/release` | `../Commander/keepercommander/__init__.py::__version__`; HEAD `63150540` ("Pam Remote Browser Get JSON response data added") at time of pin |
    13	| Bundled macOS `keeper` binary at `/Applications/Keeper Commander.app/Contents/Resources/app.asar/node_modules/.../keeper` | `17.1.14` | some operator workstations still have the older binary installed via the signed DMG |
    14	| Upstream repo | [`Keeper-Security/Commander`](https://github.com/Keeper-Security/Commander) | branch `release` is the canonical source-of-truth for this pin |
    15	
    16	The SDK works with any `keeper` binary ≥ `17.1.14`, but **requires the Python
    17	module at `17.2.13` or newer** for the in-process code paths (`pam project
    18	import`/`extend`, `_write_marker`). `CommanderCliProvider.apply_plan()` reads
    19	`importlib.metadata.version("keepercommander")` and raises `CapabilityError`
    20	before mutating the tenant when the installed wheel is below that floor (see
    21	`tests/test_commander_cli.py::test_apply_rejects_keepercommander_below_minimum`).
    22	If `pip show keepercommander` reports an older version, `apply` will fail with
    23	that gate even when the `keeper` binary is newer.
    24	
    25	## Why two versions matter
    26	
    27	Three concrete deltas that the SDK has to work around:
    28	
    29	1. **`record-update`** — Commander `17.1.14` (binary) does **not** ship a
    30	   `record-update` command. `17.2.13` adds it but the typed-field syntax
    31	   (`-cf label=value`) is unstable across patch releases. The SDK bypasses
    32	   the subcommand entirely: `_write_marker` calls `record_management.
    33	   update_record` through the in-process Python API instead.
    34	2. **`pam project import` / `pam project extend`** — subprocess invocation
    35	   cannot resume a persistent-login session for these two verbs (they
    36	   re-prompt for `User(Email):` mid-run). The SDK routes them through
    37	   `PAMProjectImportCommand.execute(params, ...)` in-process.
    38	3. **`pam gateway list` / `pam config list --format json`** — only
    39	   available on `17.2.13+` (release branch). Older binaries fall back to
    40	   ASCII tables, which the SDK no longer parses. If a downgrade is
    41	   required, re-add `_parse_ascii_table` from git history
    42	   (commit `31a8014^`).
    43	
    44	## Capabilities the SDK uses
    45	
    46	### Subprocess (via `keeper` binary)
    47	
    48	| command | used for | flags |
    49	|---------|----------|-------|
    50	| `ls <folder_uid> --format json` | `discover` listing | `--format json` |
    51	| `get <uid> --format json` | `discover` record fetch | `--format json` |
    52	| `mkdir -uf <path>` | scaffolding the `PAM Environments` tree | user-folder flag |
    53	| `mkdir -sf --manage-users --manage-records --can-edit --can-share <path>` | per-project Resources/Users shared folders | shared-folder flag |
    54	| `secrets-manager share add --app <app> --secret <sf_uid> --editable` | bind scaffolded shared folders to the gateway's KSM app | |
    55	| `pam gateway list --format json` | resolve `mode: reference_existing` gateway UID / KSM app UID | ships in `17.2.13+` |
    56	| `pam config list --format json` | resolve reference-existing PAM configuration UID | ships in `17.2.13+` |
    57	| `rm --force <uid>` | delete orphaned managed records in `apply --allow-delete` | `--force` skips the interactive confirm |
    58	
    59	### In-process (via `keepercommander` Python module)
    60	
    61	| class / function | used for |
    62	|------------------|----------|
    63	| `keepercommander.commands.pam_import.edit.PAMProjectImportCommand.execute` | create project scaffold + PAM data in one call |
    64	| `keepercommander.commands.pam_import.extend.PAMProjectExtendCommand.execute` | add resources to an existing configuration |
    65	| `keepercommander.api.login` (via `deploy_watcher.py` helper) | bootstrap a `KeeperParams` for the provider |
    66	| `keepercommander.record_management.update_record` | write the `keeper_declarative_manager` custom field |
    67	| `keepercommander.vault.KeeperRecord.load` | hydrate typed record for the marker write |
    68	| `keepercommander.vault.TypedField.new_field` | build the custom-field entry |
    69	
    70	### Post-import connection / RBI tuning field map
    71	
    72	This is the Issue #5 / Job D field map. It maps manifest fields to Commander
    73	import support vs. post-import edit hooks. It does **not** claim live support:
    74	`apply_plan()` now has offline-tested wiring that imports or extends the
    75	project, rediscovers records, resolves live Keeper UIDs, and runs mapped
    76	`pam connection edit` / `pam rbi edit` argv via `_run_cmd()`. Live tenant proof
    77	is still pending, so treat this as offline apply wiring until a smoke run proves
    78	the Commander edit path end-to-end.
    79	
