     1	"""Live-smoke scenarios — parametrise the smoke run by resource shape.
     2	
     3	Each :class:`ScenarioSpec` is the *payload* half of the smoke cycle —
     4	the identity / sandbox / verification / destroy flow is invariant and
     5	lives in ``smoke.py``. Adding a new resource type to the live-smoke
     6	matrix means adding one ``ScenarioSpec`` here, not touching the runner.
     7	
     8	A scenario provides:
     9	
    10	1. A canonical name (``pamMachine``, ``pamDatabase``, …) used on the
    11	   ``--scenario`` CLI flag and for title namespacing.
    12	2. The Keeper-side primary ``resource_type`` — must match the
    13	   ``keepercommander.commands.pam_import`` accepted strings verbatim
    14	   (see ``docs/CAPABILITY_MATRIX.md``).
    15	3. A ``build_resources(pam_config_uid_ref)`` callable that returns the
    16	   ``resources[]`` fragment for the manifest. Every resource must set
    17	   ``uid_ref``, ``title``, ``type``, and ``pam_configuration_uid_ref``
    18	   — shared by all scenarios — plus whatever type-specific fields the
    19	   upstream schema requires.
    20	4. A ``verify(records)`` callable that inspects discovered live
    21	   records and raises :class:`AssertionError` if the type-specific
    22	   post-apply invariants are violated (e.g. pamDatabase must expose
    23	   ``database_type`` on the managed payload).
    24	
    25	The live-smoke runner iterates the registry; unit tests in
    26	``tests/test_smoke_scenarios.py`` validate every scenario's manifest
    27	fragment passes schema + planner without a live tenant.
