   304	## Phase 7: Broader Keeper Surface
   305	
   306	Do not hand-code broad support from memory. Mirror upstream first.
   307	
   308	Order:
   309	
   310	1. Extend capability mirror:
   311	   - Keeper Commander non-PAM commands,
   312	   - KSM Python SDK,
   313	   - Keeper Terraform providers.
   314	2. Generic vault records:
   315	   - login records first,
   316	   - custom fields,
   317	   - file attachments only after redaction/size policy.
   318	3. Shared folders:
   319	   - create/update,
   320	   - memberships,
   321	   - permission diffs,
   322	   - destructive changes require explicit flags.
   323	4. KSM applications:
   324	   - reference existing,
   325	   - app create,
   326	   - share binding,
   327	   - client/token lifecycle with redaction.
   328	5. Teams/roles/enterprise config:
   329	   - read/validate first,
   330	   - write only with upstream-safe surfaces and strong approval gates.
   331	6. Compliance/reporting:
   332	   - start as read-only assertions in `validate --online`.
   333	
   334	Acceptance:
   335	
   336	- Every new surface enters with capability mirror evidence.
   337	- Every mutating surface has mock tests, provider tests, docs, examples, and
   338	  live smoke before support claim.
   339	
   340	## Process Plan
   341	
   342	Cursor / Codex / daybook orchestration (parent / worker split, Codex CLI
   343	wrappers, slice prompts, GitHub-Codex Action / issue template, Phase-0
   344	gate scripts) is **operator-side infrastructure** maintained canonically
   345	in the maintainer's private daybook (`msawczynk/cursor-daybook`:
   346	`docs/orchestration/` + `templates/`). It is not shipped from this repo.
   347	Adopters who want the same parent-orchestrator workflow can copy
   348	templates from there with `# adapt:` markers.
   349	
   350	### Parent Review Loop
   351	
   352	For each task:
   353	
   354	1. Read latest issue + relevant docs + latest live evidence.
   355	2. Delegate narrow offline work to Codex.
   356	3. Review diff before running broad checks.
   357	4. Run focused tests.
   358	5. Run one live proof only when the code is locally green.
   359	6. Classify result: `supported`, `preview-gated`, or `upstream-gap`.
   360	7. Update docs, scaffold, and changelog.
   361	
   362	Stop after three failed attempts on the same live blocker. Write down the exact
   363	new blocker instead of continuing speculative patches.
   364	
   365	## Definition Of Done For "SDK Complete"
   366	
   367	The SDK is complete when all are true:
   368	
   369	- GitHub install path works (git URL or release wheel/sdist; see `docs/RELEASING.md`).
